<title>PROTEUS exercises (for Section 5.2)</title>
<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-2-spencer" label="proteus-5-2-spencer">
    <introduction>
    <p>
        Consider the function defined by the rule
        <me>
            A(x) = \int_{0.5}^x f(t)\, dt
        </me>.
        In the figure below, <m>f(t)</m> is the function graphed in blue, and <m>A(3)</m> is found by computing the area shaded in gray.
        <image width="60%">
            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                       label="prefigure-5-2-spencer">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <definition>f(t)=t^3/3 - 2*t^2 + 3*t +2</definition>
                    <coordinates bbox="(-0.5,-0.5,4,4)">
                        <grid-axes xlabel="t" ylabel="y"/>
                        <area-under-curve 
                        function="f" 
                        domain="(0.5,3)" 
                        fill="lightgray" 
                        stroke="black" 
                        opacity="0.8"
                        />
                        <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
                    </coordinates>
                </diagram>
            </prefigure>
        </image>
    </p>
    </introduction>
    <task label="proteus-5-2-spencer-1">
        <statement>
            <p>
                For some small <m>\Delta x</m>, shade in the area corresponding to <m>A(3+\Delta x)</m> on the figure above. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task label="proteus-5-2-spencer-2">
        <statement>
            <p>
                As long as <m>\Delta x</m> is relatively small, <m>\Delta A = A(3+\Delta x) - A(3)</m> is well approximated by a rectangle. Draw such a rectangle on the figure above, and label its height and its width.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task label="proteus-5-2-spencer-3">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Since <m>\Delta A</m> is approximately a rectangle, <m>\Delta A</m> is approximately the product of the height and the width. Use your labels from the previous part to write an approximation for <m>\Delta A</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <response />
    </task>
    <task  label="proteus-5-2-spencer-4">
        <statement>
            <p>
                What is <m>\dfrac{\Delta A}{\Delta x}</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <response />
    </task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="proteus-5-2-matt" label="proteus-5-2-matt">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Consider the piecewise linear function <m>y=f(x)</m> defined by this graph on the interval <m>0 \leq x \leq 8</m>:
            <image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                       label="prefigure-5-2-matt">
                    <diagram dimensions="(500,300)" margins="5">
                        <definition>f(x)=x</definition>
                        <definition>g(x)=4-x</definition>
                        <definition>h(x)=x-8</definition>
                        <coordinates bbox="(-1,-3,9,3)">
                            <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                            <graph domain="(0,2)" function="f"/>
                            <graph domain="(2,6)" function="g"/>
                            <graph domain="(6,8)" function="h"/>
                        </coordinates>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image>
            Let <m>A</m> be the function defined by the rule <m>A(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x f(t)\ dt</m>.
        </p>
        <!-- Build as table full of fillins? -->
        <task label="proteus-5-2-matt-1">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Reasoning from the graph, find the values of 
                    <m>A(1)</m>,
                    <m>A(2)</m>,
                    <m>A(3)</m>,
                    <m>A(4)</m>,
                    <m>A(5)</m>,
                    <m>A(6)</m>,
                    <m>A(7)</m>, and
                    <m>A(8)</m>,
                </p>.
            </statement>
            <response />
        </task>
        <task label="proteus-5-2-matt-2">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Name two trends or patterns that you observe in the values of <m>A(x)</m> that you found in part (a).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <response />
        </task>
        <task label="proteus-5-2-matt-3">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    On the interval <m>0\leq x \leq 2</m>, do you expect the graph of <m>A(x)</m> to be constant, linear, quadratic, or something else? Why?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <response />
        </task>
    </introduction>
    
</exercise>
</exercises>